docs.abstract: The police said an attack on the pianist was not a hate crime, but social media disagreed. Now he’s considering a return to Japan.
docs.snippet: The police said an attack on the pianist was not a hate crime, but social media disagreed. Now he’s considering a return to Japan.
docs.lead_paragraph: He came to New York from Tokyo to make it as a jazz musician, and he did, landing gigs in several touring bands and leading a trio of his own. He was elegant but never flashy on the piano, always well prepared and on time.

headline.main: He Was a Rising Jazz Pianist. Then His N.Y.C. Dreams Were Shattered.

docs.abstract: The Republican Party’s slide from statewide power to irrelevance in Delaware mirrored its swerve from moderation to the fringe. Now a QAnon fan is running for the Senate.
docs.snippet: The Republican Party’s slide from statewide power to irrelevance in Delaware mirrored its swerve from moderation to the fringe. Now a QAnon fan is running for the Senate.
docs.lead_paragraph: WILMINGTON, Del. — Lauren Witzke, a dabbler in QAnon, a self-proclaimed “flat earther” and the Republican Party’s nominee in Delaware for the Senate, was exhorting her supporters last month to “Go get ’em — America First,” as they squared off against a handful of Black Lives Matter protesters.

headline.main: In Biden’s Home State, Republican Centrism Gives Way to the Fringe
headline.print_headline: In Biden’s Home State, G.O.P. Centrism Is Overtaken by Fringe

docs.abstract: Banks collected at least $13 billion in fees on Paycheck Protection Program loans, according to a New York Times analysis. But the largest lenders say costs wiped out most of what they took in.
docs.snippet: Banks collected at least $13 billion in fees on Paycheck Protection Program loans, according to a New York Times analysis. But the largest lenders say costs wiped out most of what they took in.
docs.lead_paragraph: Loath to be seen profiting from the economic disaster caused by the coronavirus, the nation’s biggest banks were quick to pledge that they would donate to charity any money earned from helping deliver the government’s signature small-business relief plan.

headline.main: Despite Billions in Fees, Banks Predict Meager Profits on P.P.P. Loans
headline.print_headline: Big Banks See No Profit From Pandemic Loan Fees

docs.abstract: It’s a scary time for body-based art. What will survive after the pandemic? As dance artists fight the old ways, a new empowerment is in the air.
docs.snippet: It’s a scary time for body-based art. What will survive after the pandemic? As dance artists fight the old ways, a new empowerment is in the air.
docs.lead_paragraph: When the coronavirus pandemic started, the first thing I did was panic. I didn’t want to bum anyone out, but it didn’t take me long to leap to a certain conclusion: With theaters and studios shutting down, the dance world would be devastated. What would come out of the ashes?

headline.main: Could Dance Be a Weapon All Over Again?
headline.print_headline: Dance Is in Ashes. Time to Arise.

docs.abstract: A presidential executive order banning the “malign ideology” of racial sensitivity training has rippled through government into academia and corporate America.
docs.snippet: A presidential executive order banning the “malign ideology” of racial sensitivity training has rippled through government into academia and corporate America.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — For the diversity consulting industry, this summer was like no other. Amid the racial reckoning spurred by the death of George Floyd, a wave of senior-level executives began to look critically at their companies, and consultants like Melanie Miller and Loretta VanPelt found themselves deluged with work.

headline.main: Trump Attack on Diversity Training Has a Quick and Chilling Effect
headline.print_headline: Trump Order On Training Chills Efforts On Diversity
